default2.5 
defaultWit
defaulthin the European Union's research funding system, the upcoming Eighth Framework Programme, Horizon 2020, is oriented around a challenge model in which funding is used to solve societal problems by bridging the gap between research and market applications, 
defaultfor example by assisting  innovative enterprises in developing breakthrough technologies into commercial products capable of succeeding in the market. By definition
default,
default this model necessitates the scoping of future challenges, which is welcome. However, detai
defaultls of how this horizon scanning will be done and who will do it remain unclear. Also unclear are the time horizons along which it will take place and the role of domestic member-state horizon scanning capabilities in informing the European process.
default2.6 
defaultAno
defaultther area of interest from a European perspective is the role of the Chief Scientific Advisor (CSA) to the President of the European Commission. This function is still new to the Commission: the first Chief Scientific Advisor, Professor Anne Glover, was ap
defaultpointed in December 2011. Though the role is still in its early stages and appears to involve little formal horizon scanning activity, one of the future roles of a stronger, more institutionalised Chief Scientific Advisor could be participation in or leade
defaultrship of European-level horizon scanning activities. To achieve this
default,
default the CSA role would have to be extended beyond the lifetime of the current President, which is currently a likelihood but not yet a certainty. Moreover, the post would have to be given gr
defaulteater resources and stronger influence in the setting of priorities for research funding and other European-wide scientific and technical activities. 
default2.7 
defaultAnother prospective player in European-wide horizon scanning activities are European-wide consortia o
defaultf science and engineering Academies, many of which leverage the unique skills and experience of their Fellowships to conduct high-quality horizon scanning domestically. For example, the European Council of Applied Sciences Technologies and Engineering (Eur
defaulto-CASE), a consortium of national engineering Academies of which the Royal Academy of Engineering is part, is working to establish avenues for advising European policy in a systematic and long-term way, using horizon scanning and other approaches to provid
defaulte timely, objective, evidence-based advise to the European Commission. The use of such consortia by the Commission would enable it to benefit from the accumulated knowledge of the EU's most senior scientists and engineer
defaults and to ensure that the advice
default 
defaultrece
defaultived 
defaultis objective and representative of a broad con
defaultstituency of European experts. 
default3. What changes could be made to improve existing horizon scanning activity? Will the recommendations made in Jon Day’s review of cross-government horizon scanning capabilit
defaulty address current shortcomings? What progress has been made implementing these?
default3.1 The Day review focus
defaultes on Cabinet Office as a potential lead and locus for horizon scanning.  This is a clear choice, and there is already good use of expert analysis withi
defaultn Cabinet Office
default. Putting Cabinet O
defaultffice at the centre of horizon scanning should 
defaultalso 
defaulthelp support cross-departmental activity
default. However the review gives less recognition to the central role of Go-Science and the CSAs than would be expected. 
defaultFor 
defaultgovernment, i
defaultt is important that the role of science and engineering in understanding future risks and assessing resilience, preparedness and risk management strategies is fully appreciated. Science and technology are not only important for technology hori
defaultzon scanning, but for identifying broader future scenarios and the factors that influence them and for dealing appropriately with the uncertainty and risk measures in horizon scanning.
default3.2 The Day review notes the role of academia and think tanks in the ho
defaultrizon scanning processes of government, and we would add that the national academies
default, research councils
default and professional bodies such as engineering institutions and learned societies also have a key role to play.
default3.3 The value of involving independent advi
defaultce in horizon scanning is that, if organisations perform their own horizon scanning, they are bound to constrain the horizon relative to their experience and knowledge of the organisation. Horizon scanning should be carried out in an environment that is op
defaulten to challenge and includes the views of those outside of the civil service and government. Improvements to existing horizon scanning capability require involvement of truly independent experts and openness to the challenges they may present. 
default3.4 As noted above, science and technology expertise is crucial for scenario planning. The solutions available 
defaultfor
default any problem are highly dependent on how the problem is specified. Narrow specifications 
defaultthat 
defaultdo not correctly incorporate uncertainty effects
default will produce solutions which are limited in their usefulness. Uncertainty is sometimes not very well incorporated in analysis and it is likely that scientists, engineers and technologists well versed with dealing with uncertainty can produce more accurate
default results.
default4. How effective is the Government at responding to policy or regulatory challenges presented by new technologies?
default4.1 There is an intrinsic challenge in creating policy and regulation for emerging technologies. 
defaultIt is difficult for regulation to 
defaultkeep pace with technology
default al
defaultthough there is very often a 
defaultneed for a 
defaultsymbiotic relationship between developing technologies and 
defaultthe 
defaultregulatory 
defaultmachinery to allow a technology to develop, such as a
defaultutonomous vehicles
default. W
defaultithout a regulatory context
default,
default it is diffi
defaultcult for industry to invest in developing products 
defaultthat
default may or may not be permitted for use.  The Academy report 
defaultAutonomous Systems: social, legal and ethical issues
default 
default(2009) 
defaultset
defaults 
defaultout this challenge.
default4.2 In the case of 3D printing however, regulation becomes necessary through the application of the technology – if it can be used to produce controlled items or infringes intellectual property rights. We would not want all technical development to be prec
defaulteded and potentially stifled by regulation but equally well we would not want the development of 
defaultother technologies
default to be held up because of the lack of it.
default&#xa0;
default 
default4.3 
defaultFor government, p
defaultarliamentary timescales and the need for primary legislation probably contri
defaultbute to this reactive position, but a robust system of horizon scanning should allow government to be better prepared for the emergence and uptake of new technologies.
